Removing observations during the lockdown periods¶

Observations from 2020-03 to 2022-02 were removed to determine if it improves the predictions. Months will be labelled instead not by the month, but by interval Month 1, Month 2 etc.

In [ ]:
trips_monthly = pd.DataFrame(trips_monthly)

# Convert the 'date_col' to datetime
trips_monthly['date_col'] = pd.to_datetime(trips_monthly['date_col'])

# Exclude rows between 2020-03-01 and 2022-02-01
trips_monthly = trips_monthly[~((trips_monthly['date_col'] >= '2020-03-01') & (trips_monthly['date_col'] <= '2022-02-01'))]

# Reset the index
trips_monthly.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# Add the 'month_interval' column
trips_monthly['month_interval'] = trips_monthly.index + 1

#Adds a new column called `month_reseq` so that the months are sequential
trips_monthly['month_reseq'] = trips_monthly['date_col']
trips_monthly.loc[trips_monthly['month_interval'] > 26, 'month_reseq'] -= pd.DateOffset(years=2)

Approach 1. Applying the ARIMA model¶

Approach 1Ai. Using Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) for all AR, I, MA combinations¶

The Root Mean Squared Error is a commonly used metric for evaluating the performance of a predictive model. It measures the average magnitude of the errors between the predicted values and the actual values of a target variable. The lower the RMSE, the better.

In [ ]:
# Identifies the typical ranges of p (autoregressive order), d (integrated order), q (moving average order)
p=range(0,12) #Typically values from 0 to 12
d=range(0,2)  #Typically values from 0 to 2
q=range(0,10)  #Typically values from 0 to 10

pdq_combination = list(itertools.product(p,d,q))
#Create empty lists for RMSE and Order
rmse=[]
order=[]

for pdq in pdq_combination:
    try:
        model = ARIMA(train_set, order=pdq).fit()
        prediction = model.predict(start=len(train_set), end=(len(trips_monthly_df)-1))
        error = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_set, prediction, squared=False))
        order.append(pdq)
        rmse.append(error)
    except:
        continue
#Sorts the RMSE outputs from smallest to highest for each combination of b, q, d
results = pd.DataFrame(index=order, data=rmse, columns=['RMSE']).sort_values(by='RMSE', ascending=True)

Conclusion

The mean squared error is less than one standard deviation from the mean of the test dataset. When the mean squared error (MSE) is less than one standard deviation from the mean of the test dataset, it does generally indicates that it is a good fit. It is certainly comparatively better than the other model runs attempted. Generally, a lower MSE indicates that the model's predictions are closer to the actual values, while a higher MSE indicates larger prediction errors.

Approach 1Bi. Using Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) for all AR, I, MA combinations¶

Information criteria, such as the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) or the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC), can be used to compare different ARIMA models. Lower values of AIC or BIC indicate a better fit, considering both the model's goodness of fit and its complexity.

  • AIC is suitable when the emphasis is on finding the best predictive model, even if it is more complex.
  • BIC is more appropriate when the emphasis is on finding a simpler model with good predictive performance and avoiding overfitting.

Based on these conditions, BIC is more appropriate in this case that balances performance without overfitting.

In [ ]:
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore') #Ignores warnings

# Identifies the typical ranges of p (autoregressive order), q (moving average order), d (integrated order)

pdq_combination.clear()
order.clear()

p = range(0, 12)
q = range(0, 10)
d = range(0, 2)

pdq_combination = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))

# Create empty lists for BIC
bic = []

# For loop that calculates the BIC for each combination
for pdq in pdq_combination:
    try:
        model = ARIMA(train_set, order=pdq).fit()
        bic_value = model.bic
        order.append(pdq)

        continue

data.columns = ['Train Set', 'Test Set', 'SARIMA Prediction']

# Reset the index
data = data.reset_index()

# Convert the 'date_col' to datetime
data['date_col'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date_col'])

# Add the 'month_interval' column
data['month_interval'] = data.index + 1

# Calculate the next month by adding one month to the previous row
data['month_deseq'] = data['date_col'].apply(lambda x: x if x <= pd.Timestamp('2020-02-01') else x + pd.DateOffset(years=2))

# Modify the DataFrame to include a combined label for rows with month_interval
data['x_label'] = data.apply(lambda row: f"{row['month_interval']} ({row['month_deseq'].strftime('%Y-%m')})" if pd.notnull(row['month_deseq'])
                         else f"{row['month_interval']}", axis=1)

Conclusions¶

There are four approaches taken with the time-series modelling:

  • Approach 1A. ARIMA Model - Optimizing for Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
  • Approach 1B. ARIMA Model - Optimizing for Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)
  • Approach 2A. SARIMA Model - Optimizing for Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
  • Approach 2B. SARIMA Model - Optimizing for Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)
